Include a brief explanation of how the domain name resolution was verified (I want to explain it through a website on the browser):
I type a website name  My browser first checks its own cache If it doesn't find the address there, it asks a DNS resolver 
If the resolver doesn't know the IP, it contacts one of the 13 Root DNS Servers They point the resolver to the correct Top Level Domain (TLD) server 
for example : the server for .org domains
This server doesn't know the final IP, but it tells the resolver which DNS server manages the domain duckdns.org.
Finally, the resolver asks that server for subdomain devops-maryam.duckdns.org This server replies with the exact IP address 
The resolver sends it back to my browser and the website loads 
